\subsection{Uniqueness of the quartic}
\label{subsec:uniqueness}
%----------------------------------------------------------------------

The eigenvalue equation \eqref{eq:masseq} is the simplest member of
the family
\begin{equation}
x^2 + f(C)\,x + g(C) = 0\,,
\label{eq:genfamily}
\end{equation}
with $f$ and $g$ linear in $C=s(s+1)$:
\begin{equation}
f(C) = f_0 + f_1\,C\,,\qquad
g(C) = g_0 + g_1\,C\,.
\label{eq:fg}
\end{equation}
This is a four-parameter family $(f_0,f_1,g_0,g_1)$.
Three structural constraints pin the polynomial to \eqref{eq:masseq}:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $f_0 = 0$: no spin-independent mass term in the linear
  coefficient.  Without this, a constant shift in $M^2$ would be
  present even at $C=0$, violating the requirement that spinless
  representations decouple from the mass equation.

\item $g_0 = 0$: masslessness at $C=0$.  When $s(s+1)=0$ the
  equation must admit $x=0$, ensuring that the scalar sector does not
  acquire mass from this mechanism alone.

\item $g_1 = -f_1$: coefficient antisymmetry.  This is the condition
  that makes the constant term the negative of the linear term
  (both proportional to~$C$), enforcing a Vieta relation
  $x_+\,x_- = -C$ that ties the product of eigenvalues to spin.
\end{enumerate}
After normalization ($f_1=1$), these three conditions fully
determine $(f_0,f_1,g_0,g_1) = (0,1,0,-1)$.  The ratio
$R = 0.22310\ldots$ then \emph{follows} as a consequence; it is
not an additional free parameter.

The constraints are algebraically natural but require
first-principles justification.  Constraint~(1) demands that the
linear coefficient is purely a spin effect---plausible if the
equation descends from a representation-theoretic eigenvalue problem.
Constraint~(2) is a consistency condition at the boundary of the
spin spectrum.  Constraint~(3) is the deepest: it asserts a
duality between the two roots that may reflect CPT or some
target-space symmetry of the underlying string.  A derivation from
the $SO(32)$ Casimir structure would close the argument.

